The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Frontpage | Jhumpa in Obama cell 
                                                                                                                                                 1                                                                                Jhumpa in Obama cell 
                                Jhumpa Lahiri                            
	Washington, Feb. 6 (PTI) US President Barack Obama has appointed Jhumpa Lahiri to his committee on the arts and humanities.        
	I am proud that these distinguished individuals will serve in my administration. The arts and the humanities enhance the vibrancy of our society, inspire us and strengthen our democracy, Obama said in a statement.        
	I look forward to working with them in the weeks and months ahead.         
	Besides the Indian American Pulitzer Prize-winning author, other appointees to the committee are Chuck Close, Fred Goldring, Sheila Johnson, Pamela Joyner and Ken Solomon.        
	Lahiris Interpreter of Maladies, a collection of short stories, has received the Pulitzer Prize, the PEN/Hemingway Award, the Addison M. Metcalf Award and the New Yorker magazines Debut of the Year award.        
	Her novel The Namesake was a New York Times Notable Book, a finalist for the Los Angeles Times Book Prize and was selected as one of the best books of the year by USA Today and Entertainment Weekly.        
	Her latest book, Unaccustomed Earth, won the Frank Connor International Short Story Award.         
	Close is a visual artist noted for the inventive techniques he uses to paint the human face.         
	Goldring co-founded the California-based entertainment law firm Goldring, Hertz and Lichtenstein, which represents global recording and performing artistes. He is also the co-founder of the entertainment strategic consultancy, MemBrain, which works with Fortune 500 companies.        
	Sheila Johnson is the founder and CEO of Salamander Hospitality and the co-founder of Black Entertainment Television. She is the only African American woman to co-own three professional sports teams.        
	Pamela Joyner is the founder of Avid Partners, LLC.         
	Ken Solomon is the chairman of Ovation TV, a national cable and satellite network.                                                                                                                                          
